iation of powerful local scribes, practiced their freedoms in written engagements with the state. Their communications laid the basis for civil society, showing how social networks commonly associated with the free market, the free press, and the voluntary association could also take root in powerful state institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBureaucracyzGermanyxHistory. 0aCivil societyzGermanyxHistory. 0aWritten communicationzGermanyxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  ablack forest.  abureaucracy.  acitizenship.  acivic culture.  acivil society.  aduchy of wurttemberg.  aeurope.  afoucault.  afree market.  afree press.  afrench revolution.  agerman history.  agerman identity.  agerman southwest.  agermany.  agovernment.  ahabermas.  ahistory.  aidentity.  aintelligenzblatt.  ainvasion.  amilitary.  amodes of power.  anapoleon.  anation.  anonfiction.  aoccupation.  aresistance.  aschorndorf.  aschreiber.  ascribes.  asocial networks.  astate authority.  astate power.  awar.  awelzheim.  awriting practices.  awriting.  awurttemberg.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023330040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092852740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520928527423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520928527/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY